Requirements

All analyses require the R software (v3.4+) for data retrieval, data processing, and summarizing model results, and the Stan software (v2.17.0) for Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC) sampling.

We also need a few packages that are not included with the base installation of R, so we begin by installing them (if necessary) and then loading them.

options(device = ifelse(.Platform$OS.type == "windows", "windows", "quartz"))
options(mc.cores = parallel::detectCores(logical = FALSE) - 1)

if(!require(rstan)) install.packages("rstan")
library(rstan) 
if(!require(salmonIPM)) devtools::install_github("ebuhle/salmonIPM")
library(salmonIPM)
if(!require(here)) install.packages("here")
library(here) 
if(!require(viridis)) install.packages("viridis")
library(viridis)
if(!require(yarrr)) install.packages("yarrr")
library(yarrr)

if(file.exists(here("analysis","results","auke_coho_ipm.RData")))
  load(here("analysis","results","auke_coho_ipm.RData"))

Load Data

We begin by reading in the fish data file assembled in Phase I. Specifically, it is a .csv file with the following columns:

  • pop: Numeric or character population ID.
  • year: Numeric variable giving the year the fish spawned (i.e., the brood year).
  • A: Spawning habitat size (either stream length or area).
  • S_tot_obs: Total number (not density) of wild and hatchery-origin spawners.
  • n_age_minAgen_age_maxAge: Multiple columns of the observed age distribution, where minAge (maxAge) is the numeral total age in years of the youngest (oldest) spawners.
  • n_W_obs: Observed frequency of natural-origin spawners.
  • n_H_obs: Observed frequency of hatchery-origin spawners.
  • fit_p_HOS: Logical or 0/1 indicating if, for each row in the data, the model should estimate p_HOS > 0.
  • F_rate: Total harvest rate (proportion) of natural-origin fish.
  • B_take_obs: Number of adults taken for hatchery broodstock.
# Coho population data
fish_data <- read.csv(here("data","auke_coho_data_1980-2019.csv"))

# Environmental covariate data
cov_raw <- read.csv(here("data","covariates_1980-2019.csv"))

# Standardize covariates for modeling
env_data <- cov_raw
env_data[,-1] <- scale(env_data[,-1])

Model Selection

Model comparison based on LOO. Unhelpful because Pareto ks are too high. We will proceed with the Ricker model for now because it gives more biologically reasonable estimates, especially for intrinsic productivity.

LL <- lapply(list(exp = fit_exp, BH = fit_BH, Ricker = fit_Ricker),
             loo::extract_log_lik, parameter_name = "LL", merge_chains = FALSE)

# Relative ESS of posterior draws of observationwise likelihood 
r_eff <- lapply(LL, function(x) relative_eff(exp(x)))

# PSIS-LOO
LOO <- lapply(1:length(LL), function(i) loo(LL[[i]], r_eff = r_eff[[i]]))
names(LOO) <- names(LL)

## Compare all three models
loo_compare(LOO)
       elpd_diff se_diff
BH      0.0       0.0   
Ricker -5.2       3.5   
exp    -6.1       4.3   
## Exponential vs. Ricker
loo_compare(LOO[c("exp","Ricker")])
       elpd_diff se_diff
Ricker  0.0       0.0   
exp    -0.9       4.4   
## Exponential vs. Beverton-Holt
loo_compare(LOO[c("exp","BH")])
    elpd_diff se_diff
BH   0.0       0.0   
exp -6.1       4.3   
## Beverton-Holt vs. Ricker
loo_compare(LOO[c("BH","Ricker")])
       elpd_diff se_diff
BH      0.0       0.0   
Ricker -5.2       3.5
